 in the past, the contributors to Wrestling with Nature examine how students of nature themselves, in various cultures and periods of history, have understood and represented their work. The aim of each chapter is to explain the content, goals, methods, practices, and institutions associated with the investigation of nature and to articulate the strengths, limitations, and boundaries of these efforts from the perspective of the researchers themselves. With contributions from experts representing different historical periods and different disciplinary specializations, this volume offers a fresh perspective on the history of science and on what it meant, in other times and places, to wrestle with nature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNatural historyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy of naturexHistory. 0aSciencexHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anature, natural world, science, scientific, scientists, religion, religious studies, history, historical contexts, beginning, start, initiation, understanding, philosophy, ancient mesopotamia, knowledge, pseudoscience, public, place, methods, technology, mathematics, math, arabic middle ages, medicine, medical, classical era, latin, research, limitations, disciplinary specialization, institutions, investigation, inquiry.1 aDear, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeilbron, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKline, Ronald R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehoux, Daryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightman, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov